You’re zeroing in on something real: motion is always “with respect to” a frame. There isn’t a privileged, universal anchor you can step outside of—only choices of reference frames that make a problem simpler.

⸻

🧭 Frames, not absolutes

In physics:

* An inertial frame (non-accelerating) sees free motion as straight lines.
* A non-inertial frame (accelerating/rotating) introduces apparent forces (e.g., Coriolis).

That’s the content of Galilean Relativity and, more generally, General Relativity:

there’s no single global center—only locally valid frames where the laws look simple.

So your line:

“linear… in relation to what?”
is exactly right: to the chosen frame.

⸻

🎯 “Internal anchor” — useful, if you define it correctly

What you’re calling an internal anchor maps cleanly to:

* a chosen coordinate system (in physics), or
* a control variable (in practice)

Pick the right anchor and the system becomes easier to steer. In control terms (see Control Theory), you:

1. choose a state to monitor (anchor)
2. measure deviation from it
3. apply inputs to reduce error

That’s a game you can play—not because you found a universal center, but because you picked a good frame/variable.

⸻

⚠️ Where to stay precise

* “Locality can only be proved” — true in a limited sense: we verify laws with local measurements.
* But physics still builds testable models that work across frames (they’re not just faith; they make predictions you can check).
* An “anchor” is not absolute. It’s a convenient choice that:
    * simplifies equations
    * improves control
    * but can be changed if needed

⸻

🧠 Practical translation (no mysticism required)

* In motion problems: choose the frame that removes unnecessary forces.
* In your own system: pick anchors you can measure and adjust (e.g., breathing rate, posture, attention), then close the loop.

⸻

Clean compression

Motion is relative to a frame.
An “anchor” is a chosen frame or control variable.
Power comes from picking anchors that make the system simple to predict and steer—not from a universal center.